This is fully* 3d printable chandelier.

  • You will need E14 lampholders and 22AWG wires. They are not printable. :)

I used my things for this project:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1292741
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1351085

Thee supports should be cut first from tubes in right angle. There is a step in diameter for reference.

Assembly:

  1. Printed nuts should be glued to small domes
  2. Small domes should be glued to three tubes
  3. Install small ring (see notes below) on center tube and install big dome on it
  4. Glue hook of your choice on center tube (see notes below)
  5. Cut wires to appropriate legth and strip insulation
  6. Tin ends of wires and connect them to lampholders
  7. Slowly push wires in tubes and screw E14 lampholders into glued nuts
  8. Install lampshade with E14 washers and fix by stock nut from lampholder
  9. Fit assembled chandelier on ceiling and connect wires
  10. Add E14 LED lamps by taste :)

That's it!

Notes:
You can select one of three hooks for particular application. I used longest one. Hook should be glued in last order.

Also I used small rubber ring from water tap repairing kit to hold dome on tube in top position.

E14 lampholders just screwed inside E14 lampholder nuts. No any glue. This will allow you to disassemble it for repair purposes. I didn't use M10x1 thread as it not strong enough.

description.text: Shape Sifter Lamp

Trying to design something in QCAD for Ponoko fabrication? Here's the flow I've used to generate Ponoko-compatible SVG files. Created for use with QCAD.
  • Tested on Mac OS X
  • Should work in Linux as-is.
  • Probably need to install Cygwin on Windows to use "sed"
  • May be adaptable for other 2D CAD tools.
    • I've chosen the Public Domain license so no one has to do silly things like credit me every single time they use the DXF files because it's a "derivative work". You're welcome to do so, but it's not expected. Aside: I wrote this a while ago but forgot to publish it. Better late than never!

Installation:

  • Copy the ponoko_dxf.zip file to /path/to/qcad/library

  • Uncompress ponoko_dxf.zip in place.

  • Launch QCAD.

  • Enable "View - Toolbars - Library Browser"

  • Confirm that the three ponoko_p{1,2,3} designs appear in your Library Browser.
    • Template Usage:

  • Create a new design in QCAD.

  • In the Library Browser, select .../ponoko_dxf/ponoko_p1

  • Click "Insert"

  • Place 181mm x 181mm border at origin.

    • Notice that more layers are now available in the Layer List

  • Enable "View - Toolbars - Property Editor"

  • Select the ponoko_p1 instance in your design.

  • Change the "Layer" property value from "0" to "SafeOrange_P1_181mm_181mm"

  • Start Drawing!
    • Preparing SVG for Ponoko:

  • Turn on/off all the layers and blocks you wish to see in your laser cut design.

  • Select "File - SVG Export"

  • Pick a .svg name for your file, e.g. mydesign.svg.

  • Open a Terminal window and apply the qcad2ponoko.sed script to convert line-widths to the proper values.
    • sed -f .../ponoko_dxf/qcad2ponoko.sed mydesign.svg > mydesign.sed.svg

  • Launch InkScape

  • Import "P1.svg" from the Ponoko InkScape Starter Kit.

  • Import "mydesign.sed.svg" and reposition to sit within the P1.svg frame.

  • Save As "mydesign.inkscape.svg"

  • Upload "mydesign.inkscape.svg" to Ponoko to get cutting!

title: LG Sunrise Mount for Makerbot Replicator 2/2X

description.text:
I created this mount to attach some very cheap cellphones to the front of my Replicator 2/2X for remote print monitoring.

I found the LG Sunrise for TracFone at Walmart for the low LOW price of $9. This low end Android phone doesn't need to be activated on a cellular network which was a huge plus for me. While the camera is pretty low end (2MP) it works great for keeping an eye on prints remotely (and is affordable enough for me to add it to all my printers!). By adding a cheap fish eye lens I get a wider view of my prints, you can find several on Amazon for under $5.

For software I added IP Webcam Pro Pro to the phones. This $4 app gives you both a web portal and IP camera access remotely. The Sunrise is able to run this 24/7 while plugged into the wall without running down the battery. With this cheap setup ($13 total) you're able to emulate IP cameras like the Dropcam for a fraction of the price.

How I Designed This

I started with dmpmassive's great Dropcam Webcam Replicator 2/2X Mount. I really like the way the mount sits flush on the top of the Replicator 2 so this was a great base for my alterations.

I then took some measurements with my calipers to approximate the shape of the Sunrise. While the shape of the mount isn't 100% fit to the back of the phone (the curves were hard to measure) it holds on to the phone very securely, and has been helping me make sure my prints are not failing (and my house is not burning down) for several months.

title: Lotus Elise GPS mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Certain Lotus Elise / Exige models have the option of a cup holder.  No up-standing Lotus owner would have opted for one.  However its inclusion needed two threaded holes to be made beneath the centre console.  We can make more of these.
Owning and driving a Lotus requires certain dedication.  Historically mounting a GPS was one of these.  To place a GPS in the traditional location (clamped to windscreen) is not possible.  The power cable interferes with the steering wheel, or the unit obscures the view of the open road.
Traditional approaches involve placing the GPS on the drivers lap, or having the passenger hold it.  The alternative is an expensive after marker modification.
This project is designed to utilise the cup holder mounting points to provide a means of safely holding a GPS or phone to the car.  
Print, make, and enjoy the experience as directions are available in finger tip distance from the gear stick.

These instructions are provided in reference to a TomTom, utilising their own suction mount. However other devices can easily be accommodated by modifying the mount carriage.
  • First acquire an Elise or similar Lotus that has provision for a cup holder.
  • Where necessary amend the mount to fix the relevant device. With the Tom Tom I was able to take the suction mount apart and produce a part that mated to it using the supplied screws.
  • Print both mount carriage and caddy.
  • Cut two 6mm dia. tubes to a length of approx 240mm. Use aluminium to remain in-keeping with the cars cut-down interior.
  • On each tube tap both ends. A drill chuck can be used to hold a tube tightly whist tapping.
  • First tap one end to a length of 8mm, then tap the other to approx. 30mm.
  • Twist the ends (tapped to a length of 8mm) in to the holes in the mount carriage.
  • Feed the ends of the tubes through the caddy, remembering to add a nut and washer at the appropriate time.
  • Use two 5mm dia bolts (minimum length 25mm) to attach the unit to the underside of the centre console.

Use for fine tuning the XY offsets of the second extruder.

Update 2016 May 3: I've been printing quite a lot of these while working on new extruders and hotends, and the time it took to print the original got quite annoying. So I've created a mini version without the numbers. It's a little harder to use but does the job and prints in under 5 minutes. Pegs are 1mm, so if you slice with 0.5mm width you should get a sensible tool path.

Update 2016 Apr 3: I added a V2 of the test which is functionally equivalent but adds a base to part1 so that I don't have to remember to add a raft each time. I also slimmed the design down a little by moving the Y axis in under the X axis, and renamed the parts to remind me which way around I normally assign them. V2 takes a little longer to print than V1, especially if you can manage without a raft, so use whichever works best for you.

Load both parts into your slicer/host software. Make sure that both are at the same XY position (some plater software will try and autoplace the two parts and mess up the alignment). In Repetier host the trick is to assign both parts to the same group using the "Object informations" dialog that pops up when you clock the cog icon to the right of the part name in the object placement tab. You also need to assign the parts to the right extruders. In Cura you need to use the "dual extrusion merge" right menu option by right-clicking on one of the parts after you load them. With Slic3r stand-alone it seems like you need to load the first part, then open the settings dialog and use the "load part..." button to associate the second part. Then assign the right extruder to each sub part in the object in the same settings dialog.

Each axis consists of 19 pairs of pegs. When the offsets are correct the middle pegs of each set will line up (the rest won't). It's best to get the offsets roughly right using a ruler or calipers, but if you're way off you can still measure the distance between the centre pegs to get started. Once the error is less than a millimetre you can find the best matching pegs and read the digit beside them. That's the correction needed in units of 0.1mm. You can either figure out the sign from the arrangement of the extruders or you can use good old trial and error :) In the photo of the V2 print (red abs and blue nylon), it looks like I need an additional .1 to .2mm of correction for both axes.

This is mostly a new design, but it is slightly based off the camera mount I use for my Nighthawk280. For it to mount well in the ET160 it gets printed in 2 pieces and then it gets sandwiched together inside the frame between the top plate and bottom plate.

The mount allows for about 12-50 degrees of tilt, finger adjustable between flights. The Sony camera it is intended to be used with is any of the plastic case compact Sony Super HAD cameras such as the "Foxeer XAT600M" from surveilazone.

IMPORTANT NOTE FOR THIS PART: Use of this mount requires that you add 2mm spacers between the top and bottom plates. This is to accommodate space for the camera to tilt down and up and not be touching the frame at all. The spacer is built into the X4rSB tray that I designed for the rear 2 bolts, For the front two, I just used some 2mm thick plastic cut down with a hole drilled through it. Also, you will likely have to trim down the interlocking nubs a touch for them to fit well.

I also made a VTX for the ET25/ET200 VTX and an X4rSB/D4rii RX tray that work well together since they share bolt down points. These other 2 parts will be online soon

description.text:
This tray is built to hold your X4rSB on the top or bottom of the top plate on the "grasshopper" Diatone ET160 frame. Please note that the two pictures show the 2 revisions of this part with the final revision being the white part that is further to the back of the quadcopter to allow for more space for wires.

This part is built to be lightweight and to compliment my other 2 parts to minimize weight. The ET160 in the pic is a sub-250g build including battery.

The part assumes that you will modify your RX so that the antennas come out the connector side of the part. This saves a lot of space in your microquad. To do this just open up your X4rsb and twist the antennas 180 degrees, then add a touch of hot glue to the connector to keep it secure and in place. The antennas will then come out right next to the pins on the RX. This part works well with my VTX tray which now has antenna guides built into it.

Helpful notes:
-If you want a small LED strip on the back of your quad, the back of this part has just enough space to mount one, check your prop clearance when doing this.

-I built in some structure that will need to be cut off.

This is my 3rd part for the ET160 and works well with the other 2. It has antenna guides built into it. You may have to print at 105% to get the antenna guides to line up perfectly depending on your shrink amount.

This part is built to be lightweight and to compliment my other 2 parts to minimize weight. The ET160 in the pic is a sub-250g build including battery.

Installation recommendations:
When using the antenna guides I recommend drilling out the guides to the desired diameter and possibly drilling or filing the top plate a touch to allow more clearance for the antennas. I use the straws from canned air for my antenna guides, so I drill out my guides so they fit snugly. Another thing I do is to drill or cut into the antenna guide from the bottom of the printed part to create a 1.5mm-ish cone shaped space underneath. This provides some wiggle room for the wire for in case there is a crash where the 3d printed part gets ripped from the frame. (This has saved my wires on my larger quad several times.)

The other 2 parts used in this build are the x4rsb tray mounted below and behind the vtx, and the sony fpv camera mount. Both are posted here on thingiverse.

A remix of mgg942's awesome Bowden adapter tool design. I modified this one to have a cutaway so that you can remove the tool if you like.

I haven't printed this model yet, so the concept remains untested. Bowden tubes for 1.75mm filament are generally 4mm OD, and the cutaway is around 4.9, so as long as the wrench is strong enough to function, I don't think there will be a fitment issue.

I've also included the RSDoc DesignSpark file that I modified the file with.

comments.text:
Great idea but I fear that disappointment lies ahead as I think that you'll find that the spring loaded plastic 'release' ring is a tad too large in diameter....
I did trial several with increasingly large hexagon bores and there may be a sweet spot which will work but I gave up as I figured that leaving the tool in place would do little harm and had the huge benefit of never getting lost!

i wanted something to put my printer in so i build it a flightcase
things i wanted:
  • it had to look cool, so no square box
  • it had to be able to print, both open and closed
  • L shaped, so i could add a spool holder
  • windows to see it print
  • less than 1/2 sheet wood (flightcase wood is very expensive, and most vendors will sell you a 4ft by 4ft sheet)
    • all in all, flightcases aren't cheap, and mine came out at 180â‚¬ with everything
    there are 2 good flightcase suppliers (adam hall and penn) about 98% of all flightcases i see at my job are from one or the other
    on this one i used adam hall material, so i'll provide you a part list from them

flightcases are not that hard to make, but this one is a bit special,
so if you are lost, take it to your local theater or P.A. firm and ask for some help. cut the wood according to the plan, you may need to add or lose 1mm depending how thick your wood is. (plan is for 10mm) nail the box together with thin nails (use closing lids in between the 2 parts of the back, see the pictures) add the closing lids
add the corner profiles (at the corners they just need to connect, no need to cut them under a angle, the ball corner will cover them)
to make them in a 135Â° angle, take a wood block of about 8 by 8 by 50 cm,
cut it half way length wise under 22,5Â°. flip it over and cut it again.
now use this in a vise to turn the 90Â° aluminium in 135Â° add the corner balls
cut out the parts to add the butterfly catches and add them
add some handles the parts i added in the parts list is for the very basic, you can go a lot further like i did, or even go way over the top.
this is what i did extra:
  • added windows (made them myself from tour label dishes and 5mm plexi)
  • added 5mm foam inside
  • made a chamber for the Power supply with spare parts and a cooling dish)
  • added 4 feet
  • added corner braces
  • added sunk in handles
  • added a dish with 2 D size holes (put a neutric usb connector in one, left the other open for later upgrades)

These windows i made myself.
You can get a smaller one that's mostly used to check the numbers of moving heads or monitor speakers, but those are to small.
What i did is buy 2 A5 tour labels (http://www.adamhall.com/en/ah_Hardware_Tour_Label_-_Dish_for_88001_Tour_Label.html)
i cut out room for them on the flightcase, but didn't mount them yet. then i sunk a border of 5mm wide and 3mm deep around the cut out part with a router. i cut 2 pieces of plexi glass to fit from the inside. then i cut the tour label frame in half on it's flat side with a angle grinder with a thin disc, so it's now only 4mm thick, and the back is gone. then install the tour lable with pop rivits that are to long, and attach a washer on the back to hold the plexi in place. finish of with a little silicone on the front, and a thin foam sheet on the inside.

description.text:
If you've got a SpinChill, you already know it is great for quickly chilling most beer or wine bottles and most cans. I do sometimes have some warm aluminum pint can/bottles on hand which do not fit in the Spin-Chill. I threw together an adapter which should fit at least the Miller Lite and Coors Light aluminum bottles (of this variety - they have a wide mouth). It's just a friction-fit design which seems to work fine.

I recommend putting the adapter into the SpinChill first, then jam the bottle into the adapter. This seems to be the most consistent and effective method of use.

You can find the Tinkercad page here. This could serve as an adapter for any non-standard vessel. Only the inner hole would need to be modified.

You can find Spin Chill on Amazon, or their website. Note that I am in no way affiliated with this company.

description.text:
Hi all, just finished building the 3dp Burner and while I'm waiting for the laser module to arrive, thought I'd have a go at a pen attachment to see how accurate it is.

This thing is very much a work in progress. it needs a lot of tweaking to get it perfect ,but it does work pretty well with the stabilo pens that I have.

here is it in action
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m-hyIKqfU7Q

Needed parts ...............

a spare Arduino . I'm using a Uno

1 x pen holder
1 x pen lifter (if you have more than 1 ,it makes it easier for quickly changing pens)
1 x 9 gram servo (Tower pro or similar)
1 x 10k resistor
a length of suitable connecting wire
M3 nuts and bolts to attach pen guide

Stabilo pens that have an 8mm diameter

hot melt glue or foam double sided sticky pad

Here is part 1 of the build
https://youtu.be/ZB_q3QXuLtg

Part 2
https://youtu.be/ffWrbR84KnI

I realize I have not shown the arduino setup yet .If you cant figure it out ,I'll have the video up in a couple of days .

.....Here are some very brief instructions

it should be easy to figure out though.

When M8 is sent through the sender app the CoolEn pin on the CNC shield goes live. This 5 volt signal is sent to the other arduino and is picked up by pin 2. This triggers the servo to rotate a few degrees to lower the pen. When M9 is sent CoolEn drops to 0v and the reverse happens.

I use Inkscape and J Tech photonics laser plug in to generate my G-code

the pen holder was made in 123d Design by autodesk so I've included the original files so you can adapt them as needed.

Disclaimer - you make this at your own risk. Im not responsible if you fry something.
It's worked perfectly for me though...

Thanks goes to Villamany for the great 3dpBurner design

description.text: Today I decided to hang my icicle lights on the house. Step one was to spend 3 hours with the 3D printer making clips so that I could quickly mount the lights on the gutter. That said I'm incredibly pleased with how revision 3 turned out. I purchased the 12' icicle lights at Sam's http://www.samsclub.com/sams/shop/product.jsp?productId=prod3600087&searchTerm=icicle%20lights they have multiple strands of wire wound together. I designed the clip so that I could pre-install them on the wire then hang them from the gutter. The gutter I have has a 0.7" wide lip on top and then bends together. The point of the story is, these clips work amazingly for my gutter and the lights I'm hanging and I hope they work great for yours, but I suggest trying it first.

There are 3 files:
IcicleLightClip_rev03.stl is the clip by itself so you can test print
IcicleLightClip_rev03_6x.stl is 6 clips placed in the build area
IcicleLightClip_rev03_6x_centered.stl has been centered on the build platform, in case you have any issues Speaking of issues, I have had some trouble printing them 6 at a time. I think I need to make some adjustments to my printer, especially lightly oiling all the ways. Each print there has been at least one of the six which bent up, the first time the part was still usable, the second time it actually dragged 2 parts and I had to discard them. I did print them all raftlessly, which may contribute to the issues I've been having. If the test print works with your lights and your gutter, then print them in large quantities. Suggest you print, pre-attach to your light strand and then hang from your gutter. That way you will spend much less time out in the cold! Merry Christmas and don't fall off of any ladders!

description.text: This part is based on the excelent http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:82533, it fixes a problem for me, where i need a small fan on the side of the extruder to keep the incoming pla filament cool and stop it from softening when heat creeps back from either the extruder motor or the hotend. This tends to cause the PLA to soften and it buckles and jams. I did not want a fixed structure as i still need access to the cavity to fiz jams. The solution was a little trinket box, altered to make it into a fan mount. The mount is fixed to the extruder by removing and reinserting the two hot end mounting bolts through the two holes provided. The Latch is still a work in progress, mine where "too fierce" and ended up broken after a few open/close cycles, so I ended up just using a small piece of tape to keep the box closed for now. I have included the openscad file for those that want to play, its based on the original trinket box, but hacked to produce the fan mount, it took about 5 prints to find a set of parameters that did not result in either a weak or fused hinge on the printrbot. DONT print with support material turned on. NOTES: this item will challenge your Printrbot simple, it has to be well setup to print this as the object is printed in one part and is 98mm wide. It wont print if you have a skirt turned on in slic3r, so turn it off. Before you print, bring your hotend up to temp, and run out 10mm of filament to get the extruder flowing. UPDATE: the latest version of slic3r (9.10) seems to have broken this item, it does not slice the hinge properly, previous versions worked fine.

description.text: Butterfly

This is a bracket to hold the spring clutch side of a standard roller blind. This was the first useful object I designed and printed on my Thing-O-Matic.
We wanted our blinds mounted inside the frame of the windows, but that meant we had to mount them "backwards" with the material rolling out on the room side of the roller. The brackets that came with the blinds were designed for mounting with the blind material rolling in against the window. We reversed the brackets left-to-right and made do, but the spring clutch had a nasty habit of coming unsprung. There are "reverse roll" brackets available, but why buy when you can build?
Functionally, this bracket is a mirror image of the original metal bracket and was designed to fit the existing mounting holes. Printed in natural ABS, it works great and looks better than the original stamped metal brackets.
I've included two versions which differ only in the distance that the support part extends from the base.
Build, mount and enjoy. It's not a particularly demanding part and I've been perfectly happy with my results using Print-O-Matic with an infill of 33% and .3mm layer height.

I saw Joel's video and really liked the design but don't have a dual extruder and I can't seem to get the stopping mid-print thing to work.

Others have remixed the original into stacking layers but you can see the red, black and white on the side so I basically sliced up the original to use the red as the front and outer rim, with the black section sitting inside this and the whites of the eyes slotting into the spaces in the black disc. I flipped the red outer over section to get a smoother finish on the front with the heated bed on the Lulzbot. I used PLA for the red and black and ABS for the white as that's all I had in white.

Laying the red section face down, I ran a bead of glue up the centre section and around the inner rim using the smallest amount to avoid squeeze out. I quickly pressed in the black disc and flipped it over to check for alignment with the red line. Once the black was glued into place, I carefully filed the white eyes slightly to fit and once they clicked into place easily, I popped them out and put a spot of glue behind them to hold them in place. My printer left a few artifacts from layer changes that I took care of with a file again.

I basically used Tinkercad with lots of box holes and cylinder holes to slice up the original, duplicating the original file and also using the remaining sections as holes, whittling it down into separate pieces.

description.text:
We print. We test. We fail.

We reprint. We test. We succeed.

We never win awards for all that effort, we don't have a Grammy.

Until now.

Introducing: The Spooly Award
You own a 3d printer. Just print your own damn award.
Download the Spooly v1 and accept the nomination!

RULES OF ENGAGEMENT:

  • Full print on FDM/FFF (This is a print suited to SLA, all SLA prints are self disqualified).
  • NO SUPPORTS
  • 1 shell, 1 roof, 1 floor, 0% infill
  • Don't cheat. Nobody likes a cheater, and every time you look at that Spooly on your shelf, it will be a reminder that you cheated. Your success wasn't one borne of horrible, devastating failure.

This isn't an impossible print, but it isn't a particularly easy print without fill, supports and shells.
It will also be quick to reveal issues in your print quality.

Whatever your results

Accept your award humbly, or like a gloating douche.
Champion your success.
Huddle up and cry in a corner over your failure.
Rue the day you ever decided to purchase that cursed printer.
Shout at it in German, stomp around, then threaten the printer by saying "If the window was larger I'd be throwing you through it you bastard!"

Seriously, don't forget to laugh. Why you mad bro? It's just plastic.
Place your Spooly Award v1 on the mantle and bask in your failure.

Really, you earned that spaghetti buddy. You earned it.

GOOD LUCK TO ALL NOMINEES!

Post your makes/fails.

description.text:
This is a headphone strap I made for my Astro A50, I have printed out the low poly version and it does fit fine, yet to test the Smooth one but it should be good.

This was made in Blender and TinkerCad, from here on in if you want to mod it then you will need to import into Blender, trust me this is actually easier then messing with the original in TinkerCad which had 50 primitives grouped!

ADJUSTING:
If you wish to make it so the straps looser over your head then use a heatgun and carefully soften the ABS (or similar) plastic and pull it to desired width(don't overdo it), this is easier to do then making many different versions for different head sizes.
(Assuming you like your headphones to be gentle on your head)

Note: Be careful with heatgun to soften and stretch the strap (if you do that) as I accidentally melted the middle headrest part a bit (still worked thought). Perhaps do it without that part in the middle first! (silly me)



This isn't a perfect design but does the job and is similar to original, the area where the ring slides in is a bit larger but doesn't appear to cause any issues. The ring should slide into the headphone screw in section without issue, just use suitable large/wide thread screws to tighten the plastic in, no need to use metal inserts really.


PS. If anyone finds something better let me know, really wish companies would share the object files for parts like this, since you can't buy replacements from what I can see.

PS2. And if someone has a HIGH DEF 3D Scanner then THAT would be the best way to get a really good object file, might be able to do that myself one day, but until then this is what you get...

description.text:
This is my 360° Gopro time lapse device, part bought part printed.

I first bought an egg timer from the shop Tiger for £2
http://www.tigerstores.co.uk/tiger_home/kitchen/egg-shaped_timer_1600221.html

I then pulled the top off and measured up the interface to the clockwork bottom and designed my own top to include the well known Gopro attachment. In order to print on my Ultimaker i split it into two parts and glued together after.

Once glued it sits nicely on the bottom part ready for your Gopro to be screwed on. 1 full turn on the egg timer is exactly an hour which it completes smoothly. There's even a handy alarm once finished.

One thing i didn't plan for but found quite by accident was the hole on the bottom of the egg timer that screws perfectly onto a standard camera tripod fitting.

Video of how smooth it is here:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lTw31RoVU7U&feature=youtu.be
